05359nam a22007935i 9781503612068DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019033251  a97815036120687 a10.1515/97815036120682doi  a(DE-B1597)563661  a(OCoLC)1112130029  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPS217.F66bY36 2020 4aPN56.R16b.Y364 2020 7aLIT0040302bisacsh04a809.9335522231 aYang, Caroline H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Peculiar Afterlife of Slavery :bThe Chinese Worker and the Minstrel Form /cCaroline H. Yang. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Chinese Question in the Early Afterlife of Slavery -- tPart One. “Earliest Pioneers” of White Literature of the West During Reconstruction -- t1. The “Heathen Chinee” and Topsy in Bret Harte’s Narratives of the West -- t2. Mark Twain’s Chinese Characters and the Fungibility of Blackness -- t3. Ambrose Bierce’s Critique of Blackface Minstrelsy and Anti-Chinese Racism -- tPart Two. “Pioneers” of Asian American and African American Literatures at the Turn of the Twentieth Century -- t4. Representations of Gender and Slavery in Sui Sin Far’s Early Fictions -- t5. Reading the Minstrel Tradition and U.S. Empire Through Charles Chesnutt’s The Marrow of Tradition -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Peculiar Afterlife of Slavery explores how antiblack racism lived on through the figure of the Chinese worker in US literature after emancipation. Drawing out the connections between this liminal figure and the formal aesthetics of blackface minstrelsy in literature of the Reconstruction and post-Reconstruction eras, Caroline H. Yang reveals the ways antiblackness structured US cultural production during a crucial moment of reconstructing and re-narrating US empire after the Civil War. Examining texts by major American writers in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries—including Harriet Beecher Stowe, Bret Harte, Mark Twain, Ambrose Bierce, Sui Sin Far, and Charles Chesnutt—Yang traces the intertwined histories of blackface minstrelsy and Chinese labor. Her bold rereading of these authors' contradictory positions on race and labor sees the figure of the Chinese worker as both hiding and making visible the legacy of slavery and antiblackness. Ultimately, The Peculiar Afterlife of Slavery shows how the Chinese worker manifests the inextricable links between US literature, slavery, and empire, as well as the indispensable role of antiblackness as a cultural form in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aForeign workers, Chinese, in literature. 0aMinstrels in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aRacism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Asian American.2bisacsh  aAmerican Literature.  aAntiblackness.  aBlackface Minstrelsy.  aChinese Exclusion.  aChinese Labor.  aComparative Racialization.  aEmpire.  aNineteenth-Century American Literature.  aReconstruction.  aSlavery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z97831